<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>How does an increase in government spending affect private consumption?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Always decreases private consumption</option>
            <option letter="b">May increase private consumption through multiplier effect</option>
            <option letter="c">Has no effect on private consumption</option>
            <option letter="d">Only affects government consumption</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Increased government spending may increase private consumption through the multiplier effect as the initial spending becomes income for others, who then spend part of their additional income.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What happens to the natural rate of interest when productivity growth increases?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Natural rate decreases</option>
            <option letter="b">Natural rate increases</option>
            <option letter="c">Natural rate stays constant</option>
            <option letter="d">Only nominal rate changes</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Higher productivity growth increases the natural rate of interest because it raises the return on capital investment, increasing the equilibrium interest rate that balances saving and investment.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>How does an increase in the capital stock affect the marginal product of labor?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Decreases marginal product of labor</option>
            <option letter="b">Increases marginal product of labor</option>
            <option letter="c">Has no effect on marginal product of labor</option>
            <option letter="d">Effect cannot be determined</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>An increase in the capital stock increases the marginal product of labor because workers have more or better capital equipment to work with, making each additional unit of labor more productive.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What happens to aggregate demand when consumers expect future prices to fall?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">AD increases</option>
            <option letter="b">AD decreases</option>
            <option letter="c">AD stays the same</option>
            <option letter="d">Only affects aggregate supply</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>When consumers expect future prices to fall, they tend to postpone purchases, leading to a decrease in current aggregate demand as they wait for lower prices.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
